 in values over time.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF TREND\":\"This example shows sales data of three products (Red, Blue, and Green) over several years, illustrating different trends: a downward trend for Blue, an upward trend for Red, and a constant trend for Green.\"", "\"SEASONAL VARIATIONS\":\"Seasonal variations\" refer to short-term fluctuations in value caused by differing circumstances affecting results at different times of the day, week, month, year, etc. These fluctuations are influenced by factors such as weather, annual events, and customer shopping habits. Seasonal variations specifically pertain to the regular intervals at which these fluctuations occur, impacting sales or other metrics. These variations are typically calculated by comparing actual sales to trend factors for each season.", "\"EXAMPLE OF SEASONAL VARIATIONS\":\"The sales for one of Leybourne Co's products over each season in the last three years show significant seasonal variations, with higher sales in summer and lower sales in winter, indicating an overall upward trend despite seasonal fluctuations.\"", "\"CYCLICAL VARIATIONS\":\"Cyclical variations are medium-term changes in values resulting from factors that repeat in cycles, such as economic cycles alternating between booms and recessions.\"", "\"MOVING AVERAGES METHOD\":\"The moving averages method removes seasonal variations from data by averaging the results of a fixed number of periods, smoothing out data sets to reveal their overall trend.\"", "\"ADDITIVE MODEL\":The additive model is a forecasting method that separates time series data into trend, seasonal, and irregular components. It assumes that the observed data is the sum of these components. The model operates under the assumption that the components of the time series are independent, meaning the trend will not affect the seasonal variations. Seasonal variations are calculated by subtracting the trend figure from the actual data.", "\"EXAMPLE OF SEASONAL VARIATIONS - ADDITIVE MODEL\":\"Frances opens a cafe from Tuesday to Saturday each week. A sales trend is calculated using a 5-day moving average, and daily variations are calculated as the difference between actual sales and the trend for each day.\"", "\"SEASONAL VARIATION\":\"Seasonal variation\" refers to the periodic fluctuations in data that occur at regular intervals due to seasonal factors. These variations can be identified and measured to adjust the data for better trend analysis. Seasonal variation is often added to trend forecasts to improve accuracy and is calculated as the difference between the actual value and the trend value. This concept is commonly applied to fluctuations in sales or other metrics, helping to provide a clearer understanding of underlying trends by accounting for predictable seasonal patterns.", "\"QUIZ: ADDITIVE MODEL\":\"This quiz involves calculating the trend and seasonal variations using the additive model based on Dewie Co's quarterly profits over three years.\"", "\"TREND AND SEASONAL VARIATION CALCULATION\":\"The process of calculating trend and seasonal variations using the multiplicative model involves determining the moving totals, moving averages, and seasonal variations for a given set of data. This method helps in understanding the underlying trend and seasonal patterns in the data.\"", "\"MULTIPLICATIVE MODEL\":\"The multiplicative model is a method used in time series analysis where the observed data is assumed to be the product of the trend, seasonal, and random components. This model is particularly useful for data with proportional seasonal variations.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}